posts.name: ezra
posts.cooked: I’ve been looking into both and will it matter which one I use I don’t belive there is any high frequency on the robot so am I fine to go unsheilded? Or is there any other upside of either.

posts.name: Ken Pontbriant
posts.cooked: Even an unshielded  Ethernet cable offers quite a bit of noise immunity due to its twisted pair construction. We’ve experienced no issues using unshielded cable (that I know about). Shielded cable is heavier and less flexible but likely more durable.
The speeds aren’t fast enough for it to matter. As long as you don’t wrap your ethernet cable around a motor like a coil.

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
EzraFalcon:

high frequency on the robot

Square pulses have significant high frequency components. (You may find this description interesting.) The PWM of voltage within the motor controllers is noisy and that’s why advice says put distance between them and susceptible devices and cables.

The sparks in brushed motors produce high frequency EMI that must be avoided somehow. Sparks are the original radio transmitters .

Ethernet itself has significant high frequency noise. Each pair considers the other pairs just noise. Each pair has a different twist rate (pitch) so that crosstalk signals tend to cancel instead of align and accumulate.

My team has not seen any problem with unshielded Ethernet cable. The short lengths and smart routing is adequate.

I would be interested in @kiettyyyy take on this. Especially with POE. Would be cool if they can analyze and recommend more specific actions than “dont have an ethernet line near a running kraken”. Instead something like “An ethernet line with PoE running through the krakens EMF will experience downstream spikes/drops under these circumstances”.

Afaik they’re the only ones who have the equipment (or hired/rented a lab) to do this kind of testing.

posts.name: FrankJ
posts.cooked: Shielded cable is kinda a pain. Not a very good bend radius and stiff. We have never used on the robot and have not had a issue.

posts.name: Chris Bale
posts.cooked: We had a lot of Limelight issues a few years back with our multiple cameras on the robot that were entirely solved by switching to shielded Ethernet cables. As a result, we use them almost exclusively on the robot now. A word of caution though, get a Ethernet tester that can detect Shielded/Unshielded cables, as many on Amazon lie.

posts.name: tkchan
posts.cooked:
just want to make sure people understands.  Shielded Ethernet cable contains a metal outer layer around all the twisted pairs.  And it requires a special connector to connect this outer layer to GROUND to make it a shielded ethernet cable.  If you don’t ground the shield, you actually can make noise/interference worst because now you are putting an antennae around your twisted bundle.

Another potential bad thing for FRC application is that if for any reason you were to ground this shield and your outer jacket got any nicked enough to expose the shielding and the shielding were to touch any metal frame, you now just grounded your metal frame and will not pass any regular inspection at all.

At the frequency and voltage level that we are operating in, there’s zero reason to use shielded ethernet at all.

posts.name: CEF
posts.cooked: Should point this out:  Ehernet and canbus are twisted pair because they use differential signaling.  The signals on the two wires are inverted, with the idea that anything that affects one wire is going to affect the other one, so if you look at the difference in the signal between the two wires, that noise will just cancel out.

posts.name: Fletcher
posts.cooked: Nothing on an FRC robot requires anything more then unshielded CAT5e.
